<font color="#FF0000">DRUGS IN NAM</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun 16  6:41:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I served for an extended period with MACV in the Delta and also with the First of the Fifth, First Air Cavalry Division.  I agree that in the field drugs were not commonly used.  My experience with the enemy however, indicates that they did use drugs in the field.  How wide spread their use was I can't say.  But enemy dead I had the chance to handle evidenced heavy use of hash or whatever the stuff was that many vilagers dried on the roofs of their huts.  Continuing to tread in this place where memory allows some of us to tread, one of the signals that alerted to the fact that possible hostile forces were in close proximity was the strong odor associated with the fish sauce they used to season their food and the drugs they used.  Acknowledging that there are Vietnamese Americans reading this I sympathize with any discomfort I may have caused by relating this aspect of my combat experience.  One of the reasons most Nam vets were so surprised by the final outcome of the war was the sure knowledge of the misery and harm we perpetuated on the enemy.  Additionally, we acknowledged and undedrstood why they used drugs in order to continue in their struggle against us.  Again, I have to admit that I'm relating to things that only combat veterans know about and understand.  Well, nuff time and space.  Corbin
